Name: DNA gyrase, A subunit
Comments: introduces negative supercoils [PUB_0171];

Comments: weak homology to rimK which is encoded by MG_012 [PUB_0110];

Name: alpha-L-glutamate ligase
Comments: adds 4 additional Glu residues to the native E. coli Glu-Glu C-terminus of ribosomal protein S6 [PUB_0110]; mutation of the first glutamate residue to lysine blocks rimK activtity [PUB_0110]; M. genitalium ribosomal protein S6 C terminus is GAKP-C';

Name: multidrug ABC transporter, ATP-binding/permease protein
Comments: no predicted substrate binding protein in M. genitalium; similar to multidrug resistant transporters of eukarya [PUB_0241, PUB_0439, PUB_0440]; functions as dimer;

Name: multidrug ABC transporter, ATP-binding/permease protein
Comments: no predicted substrate binding protein in M. genitalium; similar to multidrug resistant transporters of eukarya [PUB_0241, PUB_0439, PUB_0440]; functions as dimer;

Name: chaperone protein DnaJ
Comments: co-chaperone for dnaK [PUB_0014]; also chaperone itself [PUB_0014]; preference for hydrophobic and aromatic residues [PUB_0014]; interacts with side chains [PUB_0014];

Name: proline iminopeptidase
Comments: prolyl oligopeptidase; a/b-hydrolase fold family enzyme [PUB_0032]; cytosol aminopeptidase V [PUB_0033]; removes N-terminal amino acid, preference proline >> alanine >> other amino acids [PUB_0032]

Name: GTP-binding protein YchF
Comments: translation associated P-loop GTPase [PUB_0110]; double-stranded nucleic acid binding domain [PUB_0215]; possibly binds looped RNA [PUB_0215]; yeast ychF interacts with multisubunit translation elongation factor eEF1 [PUB_0215]; downregulated under DNA damage [PUB_0215];

Name: Beta-glycosyl transferase
Comments: Synthesize oligosaccharides, polysaccharides, and glycoconjugates by transferring the sugar moiety from an activated nucleotide-sugar donor to an acceptor molecule, which may be a growing oligosaccharide, a lipid, or a protein, for example: (malQ, coli): (glucose)n + (glucose)m  (glucose)n+m-1 + alpha-D-glucose [PUB_0110]; LPS O:3 antigen (homopolymer of 6-deoxy-L-altrose repeating units linked by 1,2 linkages) biosynthesis; NDP-sugar hexosyltransferases; group 4 nrd2 glycosyltransferases: cell surface polysaccharide (CSP) biosynthesis [PUB_0238];Suthers et al [PUB_0610] annotates MG_025 as a minor teichoic acid synthase. However evidence for this annotation is weak.

Name: transcription termination/antitermination protein NusB
Comments: may align with rsmB;rsmB catalyzes m5C967 modification of 16S rRNA [PUB_0105]; aligning base in M. gen 16S rRNA is G not C;

Name: DJ-1/PfpI family protein
Comments: involved in oxidative stress response [PUB_0110];

Name: DNA polymerase III, alpha subunit, Gram-positive type

Comments: transposon generated MG_032 transformant is cytadherent deficient [PUB_0181];

Name: Monosaccharide (riboside/galactoside) ABC transporter, substrate binding protein
PTS system, HPr
Comments: Part of the PTS [PUB_0440];

Name: spermidine/putrescine (polyamine) ABC transporter, ATP-binding protein, putative
spermidine/putrescine (polyamine) ABC transporter, permease protein, putative
spermidine/putrescine (polyamine) ABC transporter, permease protein, putative
spermidine/putrescine (polyamine) ABC transporter, spermidine/putrescine binding protein, putative
metalloendopeptidase
Comments: Putative Zn-metalloendopeptidase; also called O-sialoglycoprotein endopeptidases; may be secreted [PUB_0015]

Name: signal recognition particle protein
Comments: half-life free ffh protein 20 minutes [PUB_0399];

Name: transcription antitermination protein NusG, putative
Comments: transcription antitermination has not been reported in any mycoplasma [PUB_0182]; rho not essential in B. subtilis [PUB_0234]; the five sequenced members of the pneumoniae clade all contain most of the necessary machinery for forming an [PUB_0182]; elongation factor [PUB_0233]; supresses pause sites [PUB_0233]; simulates rate of transcription [PUB_0233]; may connect Rho to RNA polymerase-RNA complex [PUB_0233];

Name: small primase-like protein
Comments: Contain toprim domain found in bacterial primases [PUB_0202].Glass manual annotates this gene as ribonuclease MS [PUB_0764].

Name: SsrA-binding protein
Comments: Helps ssrA associate with stalled ribosomes

Name: glycosyl transferase
Comments: synthesize oligosaccharides, polysaccharides, and glycoconjugates by transferring the sugar moiety from an activated nucleotide-sugar donor to an acceptor molecule, which may be a growing oligosaccharide, a lipid, or a protein, for example (malQ, coli): (glucose)n + (glucose)m  (glucose)n+m-1 + alpha-D-glucose [PUB_0110]; essential for O-antigen biosynthesis in V. cholerae [PUB_0237]; group 6 nrd2 glycosyltransferases: abequose transferase, takes part in the formation of the O-antigen repeat unit [PUB_0238];

Name: ABC transporter, permease protein, putative
Comments: no predicted substrate binding protein in M. genitalium; macrolide-specific ABC transporter [PUB_0110];

Name: ABC transporter, ATP-binding protein
Comments: no predicted substrate binding protein in M. genitalium; macrolide-specific ABC transporter [PUB_0110];

Name: ATPase, P-type (transporting), HAD superfamily, subfamily IC
Comments: inorganic cation transport ATPase [PUB_0110, PUB_0439]; possibly transports calcium [PUB_0096, PUB_0211]; Flavobacterium odoratum p-type calcium atpase is homologous to eukaryotic sarcoplasmic reticulum p-type calcium atpase [PUB_0213]; sacroplasmic calcium p-type atpase may be catalytically active as a monomer [PUB_0214];

Name: preprotein translocase, SecA subunit
Comments: Translocates unfolding proteins into and through the cell membrane. Tomkiewicz et al observed a kinetic rate of 270 pmol aa/min for the E. coli SecA translocase [PUB_0001]. Tomkiewicz et al and Doyle et al observed an energetic cost of 20-50 aa/ATP [PUB_0002, PUB_0003]. Dalbey and von Heijne observed an energetic cost of 4-5 DA/ATP [PUB_0003].

Name: excinuclease ABC, B subunit
Comments: recognizes and cleaves damaged oligonucleotides [PUB_0072]; (1) A2B1 recognizes damage, (2) B separates DNA strands and becomes stably bound to DNA, (3) A2 hydrolyzes ATP and dissociates from B, (4) C binds and incises 12-13mer [PUB_0084];
in an operon with MG_075 [PUB_0176];

Name: 116 kDa surface antigen
Comments: immunoreactive [PUB_0176]; in an operon with MG_074 [PUB_0176];Suthers et al [PUB_0610] annotates MG_075 as a teichuronic acid synthase. However evidence for this annotation is weak.

Name: oligopeptide ABC transporter, permease protein
Comments: part of oppBCDF [PUB_0440];

Name: oligopeptide ABC transporter, ATP-binding protein
Comments: part of oppBCDF [PUB_0440];

Name: oligopeptide ABC transporter, ATP-binding protein
Comments: part of oppBCDF [PUB_0440];

Name: peptidyl-tRNA hydrolase
Comments: remove the peptide moieties from immature peptide-tRNAs released from ribosome in case of abortive protein synthesis

Name: tRNA(Ile)-lysidine synthetase
Comments: ligates lysine to cytidine to make lysidine at wobble position (34) of tRNA for AUA codon (MG486) [PUB_0047]

Name: HPr(Ser) kinase/phosphatase
Comments: Regulates HPr (PtsH, MG_041_MONOMER) by phosphorylating the protein. Phosphorylated HPr in turn senses glycolytic intermediates such as FDP and regulates carbon catabolite repression. Specifically HPr activates CcpA which in turn represses the transcription of metabolic genes and enhances the transcription of glycolytic genes [PUB_0442].

Name: prolipoprotein diacylglyceryl transferase
Comments: Transfers the N-acyl diglyceride group on what will become the N-terminal cysteine of membrane lipoproteins [PUB_0096]; prolipoprotein + L-1-phosphatidyl-glycerol  diacylglycerol prolipoprotein + sn-glycerol 1-phosphate [PUB_0266];

Name: uracil-DNA glycosylase, putative
Comments: Excises uracil bases (2'-deoxyuridine, 5'-hydroxy-2'-deoxyuridine) from DNA generated through deamination of cytosine [PUB_0072, PUB_0461].

Name: glutamyl-tRNA(Gln) and/or aspartyl-tRNA(Asn) amidotransferase, C subunit
Comments: Maybe NAD or other synthetase;

Name: glutamyl-tRNA(Gln) and/or aspartyl-tRNA(Asn) amidotransferase, A subunit
glutamyl-tRNA(Gln) and/or aspartyl-tRNA(Asn) amidotransferase, B subunit
Uncharacterized HTH-type transcriptional regulator
Comments: HTH-type transcriptional regulator [PUB_0096]; many of family are autoregulatory [PUB_0110]; regulates gluconate metabolism [PUB_0196];

Name: preprotein translocase, SecG subunit
Comments: hypothetical protein, may not be required for translocation

Name: ribonuclease R
Comments: hydrolytic exonuclease [PUB_0038]; degrades mRNAs being translated by stalled ribosomes [PUB_0019]; produces polymers 2-5 nts [PUB_0038]; processes 3' end of rRNAs, tRNAs, tmRNAs [PUB_0038]; can degrade structured RNA if toehold (e.g. poly(A) tail, which is not present in M. genalium [PUB_0041]) available [PUB_0042]

Name: putative DNA integrity scanning protein
Comments: DNA integrity checkpoint protein [PUB_0110]. In B. subtilis binds to damaged DNA and inhibits phosphorylation of the sporulation transcriptional regulator Spo0A thereby delaying sporulation [PUB_0511]. Recognizes strand breaks, base damage, and cross links, possibly through ssDNA, holiday junctions, or stalled replication forks that are generated during recombination repair of these lesions [PUB_0511, PUB_0512]. The rest of the B. subtilis signaling system (spo0A, kinA, kinE) is not present in M. genitalium.Has diadenylate cyclization activity which is abolished when bound to branched DNA such as holiday junctions [PUB_0195, PUB_0512]. Produces c-di-AMP from 2 ATPs [PUB_0512]. c-di-AMP may act as second messenger, similar to c-di-GMP to regulate Spo0A [PUB_0512].Forms octamers [PUB_0512], and is sorted to mother cell during division [PUB_0511].disA deletion has no effect on cell division, sporulation, competence, or the response of vegetative cells to DNA damage [PUB_0513].

Name: Ser/Thr protein phosphatase 2C, putative
Comments: Located next to protein kinase MG_109;

Name: serine/threonine protein kinase, putative
Comments: serine/threonine-specific and tyrosine-specific protein kinases [PUB_0110]; eukaryotic protein kinase family [PUB_0287];

Name: ribosome small subunit-dependent GTPase A
Comments: 3' maturation 16S rRNA [PUB_0101]; may play role in joining 30S and 50S subunits [PUB_0104]; depletion results in slow growth, accumulation 17S RNA [PUB_0101]; promotes dissociation of tRNA from ribosome [PUB_0102]; GTP hydrolysis promotes dissociation with ribosome [PUB_0102]; interacts with ribosome near A- and P-sites of 30S ribosome [PUB_0104]. Kinetic rate in H. sapiens 0.0005 1/s [PUB_0689].

Name: competence/damage-inducible protein CinA domain protein
Comments: In S. pneumoniae cinA is the first gene in the cinA-recA-dinF operon [PUB_0524]. There are conflicting reports on the involvement on cinA in recombination: Peterson et al report that cinA is significantly expressed during competence induction, but is not required for transformation [PUB_0525]; Martin et al report that cinA is not expressed during competence induction [PUB_0098]. CinA may function as a recombination accessory protein [PUB_0099]; CinA may be specifically required at some stage in the process of transformation [PUB_0098].
Glycosyltransferase family A [PUB_0110];
similarity to the superoxide dismutase (Mn/Fe family), C-terminal domain [PUB_0182];

Name: Cof-like hydrolase, putative
Comments: HAD-like hydrolase superfamily [PUB_0096]; most HAD proteins have phosphatase activity, e.g. g1p --> glc + pi [PUB_0108]; several HAD catalyze dehalogenase (C-halogen bond hydrolysis), phosphonatase (C-P bond hydrolysis), and -phosphoglucomutase (CO-P bond hydrolysis and intramolecular phosphoryl transfer) reactions [PUB_0108]; several additional functions have been annotated for HAD proteins -- lipopolysaccharide biosynthesis, degradation of 2-phosphoglycolate produced during DNA repair, biosynthesis of serine, detoxification, glycation repair to free proteins from the glycation products derived from direct nonenzymatic glycosylation [PUB_0108]; HAD phosphatases have broad and overlapping substrate spectra [PUB_0108]; none of the HAD proteins are essential in E. coli [PUB_0108];

Name: Spx subfamily protein
Comments: major function is to restore thiol balance under disulfide stress through transcriptional regulation [PUB_0112]; upregulatex trxA, trxB [PUB_0112]; Interferes with activator-stimulated transcription by interaction with the RNA polymerase alpha-CTD. May function to globally reduce transcription of genes involved in growth- and development-promoting processes and to increase transcription of genes involved in thiol homeostasis, during periods of extreme stress [PUB_0096]; inhibits transcription by binding to the C-terminal domain of the alpha subunit of RNAP, disrupting complex formation between RNAP and certain transcriptional activator proteins like ResD and ComA. In response to oxidative stress, Spx can also activate transcription, making it a general regulator that exerts both positive and negative control over transcription initiation [PUB_0110]; regulated by clpP protease [PUB_0111];

Name: Putative phosphotransferase enzyme glucose-specific IIB component
Comments: MG_069 has glucose IIABC activity

Name: purine nucleoside phosphoramidase
Comments: HINT (histidine triad nucleotide-binding protein) subgroup: Members of this CD belong to the superfamily of histidine triad hydrolases that act on alpha-phosphate of ribonucleotides [PUB_0110]; cleanse spontaneously adenylylated proteins (aminoacyl-AMP and acyl-AMP), a consequence of life at high temperature with high levels of ATP [PUB_0114]; involved in cell-cycle regulation in eukarya [PUB_0113]; may be cellular scavengers of inadvertently released aminoacyl-adenylates [PUB_0116]

Name: Translation elongation factor 4
Comments: GTP-binding elongation factor family [PUB_0096]; significant homology to EF-G, EF-Tu [PUB_0110]; back-translocates posttranslocational ribosomes, and the results suggest that it recognizes ribosomes after a defective translocation reaction and induces a back-translocation, thus giving EF-G a second chance to translocate the tRNAs correctly [PUB_0219]; rate of defective EF-G incorporation and translation errors increase under high ionic strength (eg. high Mg2+) [PUB_0219]; lepA improves fidelity of translation [PUB_0219];

Name: ribonuclease J
Comments: beta-CASP family [PUB_0163]; mRNA degradation ribonucleases J1/J2 [PUB_0110]; endoribonucleolytic activity similar to RNase E and 5'-to-3' exoribonucleolytic activity [PUB_0041, PUB_0165]; Cleaves the 5'-leader sequence of certain mRNAs [PUB_0096]; 5' maturation of 16S, 23S rRNA [PUB_0166]. Kinetic rate in B. subtilis 0.37 1/s [PUB_0692].

Name: 16S ribosomal rRNA
Comments: Modifications were first compiled for E. coli [PUB_0105, PUB_0119, PUB_0120], and then modifications generated by homologous enzymes were mapped onto M. genitalium by sequence alignment. Modification reaction kinetics were compiled from the primary literature (see Note_RNAModification).

Comments: Modifications were first compiled for E. coli [PUB_0105, PUB_0119, PUB_0120], and then modifications generated by homologous enzymes were mapped onto M. genitalium by sequence alignment. Modification reaction kinetics were compiled from the primary literature (see Note_RNAModification).

Name: 5S ribosomal rRNA
Comments: Modifications were first compiled for E. coli [PUB_0105, PUB_0119, PUB_0120], and then modifications generated by homologous enzymes were mapped onto M. genitalium by sequence alignment. Modification reaction kinetics were compiled from the primary literature (see Note_RNAModification).

Name: putative ATP-dependent helicase
Comments: DNA2/NAM7 helicase family [PUB_0096]; DNA2 protein is a eukaryote-specific helicasenuclease fusion that has been horizontally acquired by cyanobacteria, probably from the plant lineage [PUB_0198]; implicated in Okazaki fragment processing [PUB_0199];

Name: transcription termination factor NusA
Comments: transcription antitermination has not been reported in any mycoplasma [PUB_0182]; rho not essential in B. subtilis [PUB_0234]; the five sequenced members of the pneumoniae clade all contain most of the necessary machinery for forming an [PUB_0182]; binds RNA polymerase and promotes termination at certain RNA hairpin structures [PUB_0110]; binds Rho and RNA polymerase [PUB_0233]; helps bind Rho to elongation complex [PUB_0233]; slows RNA polymerase by enhancing pausing [PUB_0233];

Name: ribosome-binding factor A
Comments: binds 30S ribosome subunits near binding site for A- and P-site tRNAs [PUB_0104]; overlapping function with era [PUB_0104]; processes 16S RNA precursor [PUB_0105];

Name: UPF0053 protein
Comments: Hemolysins and related proteins containing CBS domains [PUB_0110]; hemolytic activity observed Mycoplasma penetrans [PUB_0185];

Name: lipoprotein, putative
Comments: activates NF-{kappa}B via TLR1/2 [PUB_0194];

Name: methionine aminopeptidase, type I
Comments: cleaves peptide bond between N-terminal methionine and C,G,A,S,T,V, or P; dinuclear metalloenzyme [PUB_0023]

Name: metal ion (cobalt) ABC transporter, ATP-binding protein, putative
Comments: no predicted substrate binding protein in M. genitalium; cobalt/nickel transporter [PUB_0113, PUB_0440]; associated with the cobalamin (vitamin B12) biosynthetic pathways [PUB_0110];

Name: metal ion (cobalt) ABC transporter, ATP-binding protein, putative
Comments: no predicted substrate binding protein in M. genitalium; cobalt/nickel transporter [PUB_0113, PUB_0440]; associated with the cobalamin (vitamin B12) biosynthetic pathways [PUB_0110];

Name: metal ion (cobalt) ABC transporter, permease protein
Comments: no predicted substrate binding protein in M. genitalium; cobalt/nickel transporter [PUB_0113, PUB_0440]; associated with the cobalamin (vitamin B12) biosynthetic pathways [PUB_0110];

Name: tRNA pseudouridine synthase A
Comments: catalyzes pseudouridation of U38-40 in anticodon stem loop [PUB_0118]

Name: oligoendopeptidase F
Comments: cleaves peptides 5-21 aa long [PUB_0035]; cleaves after hydrophobic and basic residues [PUB_0035]; broad specificity, never cleaves bonds involving acidic residues [PUB_0036]

Name: adenine-specific DNA modification methylase
Comments: MunI type II restriction/modification system methyltransferease [PUB_0098].MunI type II restriction/modification systemRecognizes the double-stranded sequence 5'-CAATTG-3' [PUB_0096], methylates the C-6 amino group of A-3 of hemimethylated DNA [PUB_0095, PUB_0096], and cleaves the C-A phosphodiester bond of unmethylated DNA [PUB_0544].Methylation occurs by transfer from S-Adenosyl-L-methionine [PUB_0544]. Methylase transferase forms dimer.Restriction is ATP-independent and Mg2+-dependent [PUB_0544].

Name: Oligosaccharide or polyol ABC transporter, substrate binding protein
Comments: Staphococcal nuclease-like protein [PUB_0110];

Name: Oligosaccharide or polyol ABC transporter, ATP-binding protein
Comments: sugar transport [PUB_0110, PUB_0439, PUB_0440]; sulfate/molybdate transport [PUB_0110];

Name: Oligosaccharide or polyol ABC transporter, permease protein
Comments: sugar transport [PUB_0110, PUB_0439, PUB_0440]; sulfate/molybdate transport [PUB_0110];

Name: Oligosaccharide or polyol ABC transporter, permease protein
Comments: sugar transport [PUB_0110, PUB_0439, PUB_0440]; sulfate/molybdate transport [PUB_0110];

Name: phosphoesterase
Comments: IntroductionMG_190 codes for DHH phosphoesterase family protein with weak homology to 5-3' ssDNA exonuclease recJ [PUB_0110]. Carvalho et al concluded in 2005 that there is no recJ in M. genitalium [PUB_0072].recJProcessive exonuclease, degrading ~1000 nt after a single binding event [PUB_0148]. DNA binding and nuclease activity of RecJ was specifically enhanced by the pre-addition of ssDNA-binding protein [PUB_0148]. Needs at least 7 ss nucleotides to bind [PUB_0148]. Exonuclease activity can be terminated by ds region [PUB_0148]. Releases mononucleotides [PUB_0148]. Possibly has exonuclease activity required to produce a free 3' single-stranded DNA to which RecA can bind for the initiation of homologous recombination [PUB_0147]. Exonuclease activity requires Mg2+, Mn2+, or Co2+ [PUB_0552]. Yamagata et al observed the exonuclease kinetics for the complete protein: kcat=2_10-3 1/s, Km=4.1 _M, and for a truncated protein: kcat>130 1/s, Km=6.1 μM [PUB_0552].

Name: MgPa adhesin
Comments: clustered at tip organelle [PUB_0088]; no cysteines, therefore very flexible [PUB_0088]; high proline content may assist in topological organization [PUB_0088]; required for adhesion and terminal organelle [PUB_0090]; P140, P110 reciprocally stabilize each other [PUB_0090]; appears to be directly involved in adhesion [PUB_0405];

Name: P110 protein
Comments: required for adhesion and terminal organelle [PUB_0090]; not post-translationally cleaved as in M. pneumoniae [PUB_0090]; P140, P110 reciprocally stabilize each other [PUB_0090];

Name: ribonuclease HIII, putative, frameshift
Comments: endolytically cleaves RNA from hybrid DNA-RNA molecules

Name: co-chaperone GrpE
Comments: catalyzes release of peptide from peptide-DnaK-ADP complex [PUB_0014];

Name: DNA topoisomerase IV, A subunit
Comments: type II topoisomerase [PUB_0171]; relax positive supercoils [PUB_0171]; unlinks DNA following replication [PUB_0171];

Name: heat-inducible transcription repressor HrcA, putative
Comments: oligomer represses transcription of promoters with CIRCE inverted repeat [PUB_0204, PUB_0206]; CIRCE sequences: 5'-aaaatatttt-N(9)-aaactaattt-3', 4 nt from start codon of regulated genes [PUB_0207]; positively regulated by groEL [PUB_0205]; reducing agents, heat promote dissociation of oligomers to monomers [PUB_0206]; only active as repressor in dimer form [PUB_0206]; present most as tetramer -- dimer 6%, tetramer 50%, octamer 31%, hexadecamer 5% [PUB_0206]; found in membrane fraction, may an integral membrane protein [PUB_0206]; acts as a reductionoxidation sensor via a Ca2+-induced conformational rearrangement resulting in oligomerization [PUB_0206];

Name: glycoprotease
Comments: Putative Zn-metalloendopeptidase; also called O-sialoglycoprotein endopeptidases; may be secreted [PUB_0015]

Name: 23S rRNA pseudouridine synthase; U955, U2504, U2580
Comments: catalyzes pseudouridation of U955, U2504, U2580 in 23S rRNA [PUB_0105, PUB_0119];

Name: prolipoprotein signal peptidase, signal peptidase II

Comments: DivIVA domain [PUB_0110];

Name: segregation and condensation protein A
Comments: in B. subtilis forms a complex with scpB and smc (scpA:scpB:smc::1:2:2) [PUB_0337];

Name: segregation and condensation protein B
Comments: in B. subtilis forms a complex with scpB and smc (scpA:scpB:smc::1:2:2) [PUB_0337];

Name: P65 adhesin
Comments: required for adhesion and terminal organelle [PUB_0092]; may be directly involved in adhesion [PUB_0405];

Name: high molecular weight cytadherence accessory protein 2
Comments: required for property function of adhesins, may help localize adhesins to tip organelle, part of the cytoskeleton-like Triton shell [PUB_0088]; protein not detectable in M. genitalium [PUB_0091]; homologous to the filamentous coiled-coil portion of myosin type II heavy chain [PUB_0093]; high Pro content, low pI, central acidic Pro-rich domain [PUB_0089]; required for gliding [PUB_0091]; Pich et al showed that MG_218 codes for two proteins -- HMW2 and HMW2-s [PUB_0803]; the M. pneumoniae homolog has also been showed to code for two proteins [PUB_0804]. Pich et al also showed that MG_218 knockouts exhibit reduced gliding motility and that the MG_218 N-terminus is required for proper terminal organelle architecture [PUB_0803].

Name: S-adenosyl-methyltransferase MraW
Comments: membrane located substrates [PUB_0126]; in E. coli in an operon that encodes genes involved in cell wall metabolism and cell division, suggesting that the target of MraW may be involved in these cellular events [PUB_0127]; lack of S-adenosylmethionine (SAM) leads to a cell division defect in E. coli, with one possible explanation being that SAM serves as a methyl donor in a required methylation event [PUB_0128]; possibly modifies FtsL and/or FtsI proteins [PUB_0128]; methylation not observed in Mycoplasma pneumoniae [PUB_0285];
part of conserved cell division cluster (mraZ-mraW-orfX-ftsZ) [PUB_0187]; however orfX genes have low sequence similarity to each other [PUB_0187];

Name: cell division protein FtsZ
Comments: Benders et al characterized the transcription initiation and termination locations points of the ftsZ cell division 6 gene transcription unit, and quantitated the steady-state RNA level for each gene [PUB_0817]. Benders et al suggest cotranscription is common is M. genitalium [PUB_0817].

Name: amino acid-polyamine-organocation (APC) permease
Comments: amino acid transport [PUB_0110]; may be catalytic as monomer [PUB_0245] or as dimer [PUB_0246];

Name: amino acid-polyamine-organocation (APC) permease
Comments: amino acid transport [PUB_0110]; may be catalytic as monomer [PUB_0245] or as dimer [PUB_0246];

Name: ribonucleotide reductase stimulatory protein
Comments: NrdI is a flavodoxin that mediates the generation of a cofactor of NrdEF (MG_229, MG_231), a ribonucleotide reductase (rnr) which catalyzes the conversion of nucleotides to deoxyribonucleotides [PUB_0159]. NrdI increases the activity of rnr [PUB_0159]. NrdI catalyzes two step reduction of NrdF subunits of rnr needed to recycle rnr [PUB_0160].

Name: apurinic endonuclease
Comments: 5' apurinic site endonuclease [PUB_0072]; can repair strand breaks in DNA [PUB_0072]; FPG glycosylase generates AP sites [PUB_0072];

Name: ferric uptake repressor
Comments: HTH_ARSR Super-family of metal regulated homodimeric transcriptional repressors [PUB_0110]; homologous to ferric uptake regulation protein (fur) of M. pneumoniae;

Name: trigger factor
Comments: Trigger factor binds translating ribosomes [PUB_0005]:Trigger factor concentration: 50 μMRibosome concentration: 30 μMTrigger factor-50S ribosome: KD=1 μMTrigger factor-trigger factor: KD=1-2 μMTrigger factor binds ribosome 10 sTrigger factor remains bound to polypeptide for up to 35 more seconds after dissociates from ribosome

Name: ATP-dependent protease La
Comments: Degrades peptides processively in either direction (EC 3.4.21.53) [PUB_0029], producing oligopeptides of 5-30 residues [PUB_0029]. Preferentially cleaves hydrophobic residues adjacent to scissile bond [PUB_0029]. Recognizes ssrA tag -- AANDENYALAA. 1 ATP binds per subunit.Also has chaperone-like activity for complexes [PUB_0029].

Name: 3-5' helicase
Comments: PcrA is a 3-5' helicase that removes oligonucleotides cleaved by UvrABC during nucleotide excision repair [PUB_0072]. Oligonucleotide excision is powered by ATP hydrolysis [PUB_0531]. Several groups have studied PcrA energetics and kinetics. Wigley report that 1-23 bases are excised per ATP [PUB_0541]; Tomko et al report that PcrA catalyzes excision at the rate 193 nt/s and 1 ATP/nt [PUB_0516]. PcrA is active as a dimer [PUB_0541].Additionally, PcrA may play a role in the initiation of recombination repair with pol I exonuclease [PUB_0072].pcrA is also homologous to recB [PUB_0072].
Rossmann-fold NAD(P)(+)-binding proteins [PUB_0110];

Name: DNA primase
Comments: 3 primase bind each dnaB helicase [PUB_0201];

Name: 23S rRNA methyltransferase; G2251
Comments: catalyzes 2'-O methyltransfer of Gm2251 modification of 23S rRNA [PUB_0105];

Comments: binds ribosome is occupied by non-sense, stop, or misincorporated codons; ribosome error rate 6 x 10^-4 - 5 x 10^-3 [PUB_0027, PUB_0028]

Name: lipoprotein, putative
Comments: Suthers et al [PUB_0610] annotate MG_260 with EC-1.1.99.5. However EC-1.1.99.5 is obsolete. EC-1.1.99.5 has been transferred to EC-1.1.5.3 which best matches MG_039 and E. coli glpA-D. The best BLAST match of MG_260 to E. coli is "probable adhesion" gene b1978. The best blast match of glpD is MG_039.

Name: polI-like 5'-3' exonuclease, putative
Comments: polI-like 5'-3' exonuclease [PUB_0072] possibly responsible for DNA resection in the initiation of homologous recombination repair. Homologous recombination is most efficient for overhang lengths of at least 8 bases [PUB_0526].Also has weak homology to flap endonucleases involved in long-patch base excision repair.

Name: formamidopyrimidine-DNA glycosylase
Comments: IntroductionHas both glycosylase and &beta-lyase activity [PUB_0073]. Participates in base excision repair of oxidatively (free radical or reactive oxygen species) damaged DNA bases [PUB_0073]. Glycosylate activityGlycosylate activity excises several types of oxidized purines and pyrimidines [PUB_0072, PUB_0461, PUB_0073, PUB_0518, PUB_0519, PUB_0520, PUB_00473, PUB_0522]:8-oxo-guanine (oxo8GN)8-oxo-adenine (oxo8AD)N6-(2-Deoxy-_,_-d-erythro-pentofuranosyl)-2,6-diamino-4-hydroxy-5-formamidopyrimidine (FAPyGN)4,6-diamino-5-N-formamidopyrimidine (FAPyAD) _-lyase activity_-lyase activity cleaves phosphodiester bond on 3' side of AP sites [PUB_0073].

Name: Cof-like hydrolase
Comments: HAD-like hydrolase superfamily [PUB_0096]; most HAD proteins have phosphatase activity [PUB_0108]; several HAD catalyze dehalogenase (C-halogen bond hydrolysis), phosphonatase (C-P bond hydrolysis), and -phosphoglucomutase (CO-P bond hydrolysis and intramolecular phosphoryl transfer) reactions [PUB_0108]; several additional functions have been annotated for HAD proteins -- lipopolysaccharide biosynthesis, degradation of 2-phosphoglycolate produced during DNA repair, biosynthesis of serine, detoxification, glycation repair to free proteins from the glycation products derived from direct nonenzymatic glycosylation [PUB_0108]; HAD phosphatases have broad and overlapping substrate spectra [PUB_0108]; none of the HAD proteins are essential in E. coli [PUB_0108];

Name: dephospho-CoA kinase
Comments: First annotation was GND [PUB_0057]; this gene is probably expressed but no GND activity detected [PUB_0444];

Name: sugar phosphatase
Comments: HAD-like hydrolase superfamily, HAD phosphatase [PUB_0106]; HAD phosphatases have broad and overlapping substrate spectra [PUB_0108]; most HAD proteins have phosphatase activity [PUB_0108]; several HAD catalyze dehalogenase (C-halogen bond hydrolysis), phosphonatase (C-P bond hydrolysis), and -phosphoglucomutase (CO-P bond hydrolysis and intramolecular phosphoryl transfer) reactions [PUB_0108]; several additional functions have been annotated for HAD proteins -- lipopolysaccharide biosynthesis, degradation of 2-phosphoglycolate produced during DNA repair, biosynthesis of serine, detoxification, glycation repair to free proteins from the glycation products derived from direct nonenzymatic glycosylation [PUB_0108]; HAD phosphatases have broad and overlapping substrate spectra [PUB_0108]; none of the HAD proteins are essential in E. coli [PUB_0108];
similar to deoxynucleoside kinase (dnk) [PUB_0182, PUB_0190]; catalyzes the phosphorylation of deoxyribonucleosides to yield corresponding monophosphates (dNMPs) [PUB_0110];

Name: scRNA, signal recognition particle 4.5S RNA, MCS1
Comments: Half-live ≫ 10 minutes [PUB_0397]. Half-lives of sRNA span great range, 60 min for housekeeping and regulatory genes [PUB_0398]. Expression 25% that of ribosomes [PUB_0401].

Name: lipoyltransferase/lipoate-protein ligase, putative
Comments: Catalyzes both the ATP-dependent activation of exogenously supplied lipoate to lipoyl-AMP and the transfer of the activated lipoyl onto the lipoyl domains of lipoate-dependent enzymes [PUB_0110];

Name: pyruvate dehydrogenase component E1, beta subunit
pyruvate dehydrogenase component E1, alpha subunit
Protein-export membrane protein secDF
Comments: homologous to secDF of M. pneumoniae, B. subtilis [PUB_0169]; secDF increases efficiency of translocase; annotated as gerBB in 1995 Science annotation [PUB_0057]; however mycoplasmas don't form spores [PUB_0168]; gerB is receptor for nutrient-triggered germination [PUB_0167]; together with gerK responds to l-asparagine, glucose, fructose, and K+ [PUB_0167]; triggers release of DPA which triggers enzymes which initiate hydrolysis of spore's peptidoglycan cortex leading to completion of germination [PUB_0167]; also transduces pressure to trigger germination [PUB_0167]; interacts 1:1 with secYEG [PUB_0328];

Name: GTP diphosphokinase
Comments: produces (p)ppGpp under starvation conditions (stringent response) [PUB_0149]; ppGpp in turn regulates transcription of rRNA and tRNA, translation, and replication [PUB_0149]; ACP interacts with spoT to shift equlibrium toward (p)ppGpp and away from GTP/GDP and pyrophosphate [PUB_0149]; ribosome-associated (p)ppGpp synthetase responding mainly to uncharged tRNAs that accumulate and binds to ribosomes A-site  as a result of amino acid limitation [PUB_0150]; recognizes stalled ribosomes and synthesizes ppGpp [PUB_0153]; ppGpp binds in the secondary channel of RNA polymerase and prevents transcription of tRNA, rRNA [PUB_0151]; ppGpp promotes transcription of amino acid biosynthesis genes [PUB_0151]; ppGpp inhibits DNA primase [PUB_0152];

Comments: In many bacteria participates in multicomponent signaling systems that regulate chemotaxis [PUB_0456, PUB_0457]. Specifically, htrII participates in the pathway: SRII -> HtrII -> CheAW -> CheY -> flagella which helps bacteria avoid photooxidative damage in conditions of bright blue light (

Comments: homologous to protein L [PUB_0057]; 2-oxoacid dehydrogenases E3 subunit; protein L is type II Ig binding receptor [PUB_0171]; binds light chain, preferably of kappa type [PUB_0171, PUB_0172]; protects bacteria from Neutrophils [PUB_0172]; light chain binding proteins have been identified in M. hominis and M. arginini [PUB_0173];

Comments: phosphonates can be used in membranes, or degraded for growth, or to chelate metals;

phosphonate ABC transporter, permease protein (P69), putative
putative holliday junction resolvase
Comments: Mycoplasmas lack ruvC and rusA [PUB_0083]. Could be a resolvase non-homologous to ruvC or rusA [PUB_0083].Glass manual annotates this gene as RNase H domain protein, YqgF family [PUB_0764].

Comments: based on homolgy, may be proton-driven sugar phosphate uptake system [PUB_0006];

Comments: catalyzes 2-thiouridination (s2U34) of wobble position (34) [PUB_0045]; hypermodification increases efficiency of wobble recognition for Lys, Gln, Glu [PUB_0047];

Comments: in B. subtilis forms a complex with scpB and smc (scpA:scpB:smc::1:2:2) [PUB_0337];

Comments: interacts with backbone [PUB_0014]; binds short, linear, unfolded, hydrophobic peptide segments [PUB_0014]; ATP hydrolysis regulated by co-chaperone grpE [PUB_0014];  Several rounds of ATP- dependent interactions between dnaJ, dnaK and grpE are required for fully efficient folding [PUB_0096]; 1 DnaK monomer: 1 DnaJ dimer: 1 GrpE dimer [PUB_0230];

Name: lipoprotein, putative
Comments: activates NF-{kappa}B via TLR2/6 [PUB_0194];

Comments: required for property function of adhesins, may help localize adhesins to tip organelle, part of the cytoskeleton-like Triton shell [PUB_0088]; high Pro content, low pI, central acidic Pro-rich domain [PUB_0089]; required for gliding [PUB_0091];

Name: DNA polymerase III, delta subunit, putative
DNA internalization-related competence protein ComEC/Rec2
Comments: may transport DNA across cell membrane [PUB_0110]; one strand is transported through comEC channel, second stand is degraded [PUB_0412]; comE has non-sequence specific DNA binding activity in N. gonorrhoeae [PUB_0177]; necessary for competence in N. gornorrhoaea [PUB_0177]; necessary for DNA uptake in B. subtilis [PUB_0178]; may be an aqueous DNA channel [PUB_0178]; however other competence proteins (comFA, ATPase; comEA, DNA binding protein) are absent in M. genitalium;

Comments: clustered at tip organelle [PUB_0088]; no cysteines, therefore very flexible [PUB_0088]; high proline content may assist in topological organization [PUB_0088]; appears to be directly involved in adhesion [PUB_0405];

Name: Rnase P RNA, MCS5, M1 RNA
Comments: Peters et al performed a phylogenic analysis of RNaseP from several haemoplasma and Mycoplasma species [PUB_0823].

Name: transfer-messenger RNA, tmRNA, MCS6, 10Sa RNA
Comments: Has tRNA-like structure with an mRNA-like domain. The tRNA-like domain is charged by alanyl tRNA synthetase and with the help of SmpB (MG_059_MONOMER) replaces the tRNA of stalled ribosomes (ribosomes stalled for example due to mRNA damage, mRNA lacking a stop codon, rare codons, or natural stall sequences), adding an alanine to the stalled peptide. Next the mRNA-like domain is translated by the ribosome add the C-terminal amino acid sequence DKENNEVLVEPNLIINQQASVNFAFA to the stalled peptide [PUB_0020]. The added C-terminal tag marks the peptide for degradation [PUB_0014].MG_0004 has a half-life of 89 min [PUB_0396]. The expression of MG_0004 is 5% that of 5S RNA [PUB_0400].

Name: degV family protein
Comments: molecular function of fatty-acid binding and may play a role in the cellular functions of fatty acid transport or metabolism [PUB_0110]; may have kinase activity [PUB_0154];

Name: hydrolase, Putative esterase/lipase 2
Comments: lipase/esterase LIP3/bchO family [PUB_0096]; protoporphyrin IX magnesium chelatase (EC 4.99.1.-) bchO homolog [PUB_0109];

Name: coiled coil putative structural protein involved in cytoskeleton
GTP-binding protein engA
Comments: ribosome stabilization [PUB_0058]; era/mnmE/trmE subfamily; helps incorporate L16, L27, L36 protein into 50S ribosome [PUB_0223, PUB_0104]; 23S rRNA maturation [PUB_0223];
negatively regulates the quorum-sensing response regulator pqsR of the PQS system in Pseudomonas aeruginosa by binding at its promoter region [PUB_0180]; highly conserved protein [PUB_0180];

Name: FMN-dependent NADH-azoreductase, putative
Comments: FMN-dependent NADH-azoreductase [PUB_0096]; catalyze reductive cleavage of azo groups (-N=N-) under mild conditions [PUB_0231]; reduces electrophilic quinones [PUB_0232]; electrophilic quinones can form S-adducts through covalent bonds with cellular thiols by Michael addition, which depletes cellular thiols and causes thiol-specific stress in cells [PUB_0232];

Name: GTP-binding protein engB, putative
Comments: protein biosynthesis [PUB_0058]; ribosome biosynthesis [PUB_0110]; B. subtilis ortholog necessary for cell division and septation [PUB_0182]; helps incorporate L16, L26, and L36 into 50S ribosome [PUB_0223, PUB_0104];

Name: glycosyl transferase, group 2 family protein
Comments: synthesize oligosaccharides, polysaccharides, and glycoconjugates by transferring the sugar moiety from an activated nucleotide-sugar donor to an acceptor molecule, which may be a growing oligosaccharide, a lipid, or a protein [PUB_0110];

Name: cysteine desulfurase
Comments: pyridoxal 5'-phosphate (PLP)-dependent enzyme that catalyze the desulfuration of cysteine to alanine and elemental sulfur
NifU-like N terminal domain [PUB_0110]; nif genes are responsible for nitrogen fixation, but are also found in bacteria that do not fix nitrogen [PUB_0110];

Name: recombination protein, strand exchange
Comments: Binds 3' ssDNA overhangs [PUB_0072]. Approximately one monomer binds ssDNA per 3 nt [PUB_0082]. Initial DNA binding promoted by SSB, then displaces SSB [PUB_0082]. Subsequent binding is cooperative and forms sprial filament [PUB_0082]. Aligns homologous DNA, and executes strand exchange forming Holliday junctions [PUB_0082]. ATP-hydrolysis appears to be required for strand exchange, although the exact energetic coupling of ATP hydrolysis to strand exchange is unknown [PUB_0529]. Strand exchange kinetics have been studied by Bazemore et al (0.05-0.07 1/s) [PUB_0528], Xiao et al (0.053-0.42) [PUB_0529], and Bhattacharyya et al (0.082 1/min) [PUB_0530].Knockouts grew faster than wild-type [PUB_0193].

Name: NADPH-dependent FMN reductase domain protein
Comments: Assumed a promiscuous enzyme like in coli;

Name: hydrolase, Putative esterase/lipase 3
Comments: lipase/esterase LIP3/bchO family [PUB_0096];

Name: 23S rRNA methyltransferase; U2552
Comments: catalyzes 2'-O methyltransfer of 23S rRNA U2552 => Um [PUB_0120];

Name: tRNA (guanine-N(7)-)-methyltransferase
Comments: catalyzes position 46 (m7G46) in tRNA with 44-48 sequence NNGPyPy where N={A,C,G,T}, Py={C,T} [PUB_0052]

Name: Holliday junction endonuclease
Comments: RuvC is an endonuclease that resolves Holliday junctions (HJ), producing two nicked dsDNA species which can be directly repaired by DNA ligase [PUB_0539]. HJ resolvases are typically small, homodimeric, metal-dependent enzymes [PUB_0539].recU belongs to nuclease superfamily of HJ resolvases whereas ruvC belongs to the integrase superfamily [PUB_0539].RuvC binds Holliday junctions with high specificity [PUB_0539]. RuvC preferentially resolves Holliday junctions at the sequence 5'-(A/T)TT_(G/C)-3' [PUB_0532]. RuvC resolves Holliday junctions with rate 0.209 1/min [PUB_0540].RuvC is hypothesized to cleave HJs with an SN2-like mechanism [PUB_0539]. The exact mechanism of HJ cleavage is unknown [PUB_0539]. It is hypothesized that one metal ion acts as a base to deprotonate the water molecule, while the second metal ion coordinates a water molecule to protonate the leaving 3-oxyanion group [PUB_0539]. Both metal ions are hypothesized to stabilize the negatively charged pentavalent transition state [PUB_0539].

Name: DNA-binding protein HU, putative
Comments: IntroductionWeakly homologous to DNA-binding protein HU.Canonical HUHU binds circular DNA non-specifically with a Kd of 2002500 nM and bends DNA, possibly compacting DNA and regulating gene expression [PUB_0085, PUB_0086]. HU forms a homodimer [PUB_0085]. 8-10 HU dimers bind per 275 bp DNA [PUB_0085]. HU condenses DNA 2.4 × [PUB_0085].HU has also been implicated in recombination and may preferentially bind holiday junctions. HU constrains negative supercoils [PUB_0086], introduces negative supercoils in the presence of nicking-closing enzyme [PUB_0085], and may preferentially binds negatively supercoiled DNA [PUB_0086]. May be regions of chromosome bound by little HU, may be concentrated around periphery of nucleoid [PUB_0087].

Name: ATP-dependent Clp protease, ATPase subunit
Comments: Resolubilize protein aggregates; no proteolytic activity [PUB_0014]

Name: Holliday junction DNA helicase
Comments: holliday junction migration

Name: Holliday junction DNA helicase RuvB
Comments: holliday junction migration

Name: ImpB/MucB/SamB family protein
Comments: low fidelity DNA polymerase [PUB_0136]; translesion DNA synthesis [PUB_0136]; activated by umuD, recA, SSB [PUB_0137];  polymerizes 1 base per binding event [PUB_0138]; mismatch incorporation rate 100-1000 X slower than correct match incorporation rate [PUB_0139]; allows cells to survive in the presence of relatively high levels of replication-inhibiting DNA damage, but at the cost of an increased mutation rate [PUB_0140];

Name: Replication initiation/membrane attachment protein
Comments: homologous to Oenococcus oeni mobilization protein mobC [PUB_0057]; mobC involved in conjugal transfer of plasmids [PUB_0174]; part of relaxase family of strand separating proteins [PUB_0174]; 0.0% horizontally acquired DNA present in M. genitalium [PUB_0175];

Name: ribonuclease III
Comments: Double-stranded specific endonuclease [PUB_0038, PUB_0039]. Matures rRNA and scRNA [PUB_0039]. Specifically, ribonuclease III cleaves precursor 30S rRNA to 5S, 16S, and 23S precursors [PUB_0038], which are further processed by ribonuclease J and rgsA [PUB_0039]. Ribonuclese II also cleaves scRNA precursor at two sites [PUB_0042].Ribonuclease II may also cleave the 3' of tRNA precursors [PUB_0044], and may initiate the degradation of mRNAs by cleaving 5' UTR [PUB_0039].Kinetic rate in E. coli 7.7 1/s [PUB_0691].

Name: fatty acid/phospholipid synthesis protein PlsX
Comments: same as plsB in coli [PUB_0446];

Name: 23S rRNA pseudouridine synthase; U1911, U1915, U1917
Comments: catalyzes pseudouridation of U1911, U1915, U1917 in 23S rRNA [PUB_0105, PUB_0120];

Name: DHH family protein
Comments: Exopolyphosphatase-related proteins [PUB_0110]; DHH phosphoesterase family [PUB_0110]; family includes drosophila prune protein and recJ [PUB_0162]; family has broad spectrum of targets [PUB_0162];

Name: thiamine biosynthesis/tRNA modification protein ThiI
Comments: catalyzes 4-thiouridination [PUB_0062]; sulfur transferred onto ThiI by IscS [PUB_0062]; modification not required [PUB_0063]; Mycoplasma doesn't contain IscS, contains similar nifS [PUB_0066];

OB protein fold (oligonucleotide/oligosaccharide/oligopeptide binding fold) family[PUB_0191]; most similar in structure to the Escherichia coli PriB [PUB_0191]; bind and stabilize transiently formed single-stranded DNA [PUB_0191];

Name: tRNA uridine 5-carboxymethylaminomethyl modification enzyme GidA
Comments: involved in mnm(5)s(2)U modification of the wobble uridine [PUB_0110]; hypermodification increases efficiency of wobble recognition for Lys, Gln, Glu [PUB_0047]; proposed biosynthesis: s2U + 5-formyl tetrahydrofolate + glycine + FADH2 ==> cmnm5s2U + H2O + FAD [PUB_0265];

Name: methyltransferase GidB
Comments: catalyzes m7G527 modification of 16S rRNA [PUB_0105];

Modifications were first compiled for E. coli [PUB_0045, PUB_0047, PUB_0055, PUB_0056, PUB_0064, PUB_0065], and then modifications generated by homologous enzymes were mapped onto M. genitalium by sequence alignment. Modification reaction kinetics were compiled from the primary literature (See Note_RNAModification).

Name: GTPase1 Obg
Comments: 50S ribosome maturation [PUB_0058, PUB_0104]; chromosome separation [PUB_0104]; may coordinate translation status with replication by linking (p)ppGpp levels to 50S ribosome assembly [PUB_0104]; stabilizes stalled replication forks [PUB_0152]; regulate and coordinate ribosome function, cell cycle activity, and DNA partitioning and segregation [PUB_0182]; possibly involved in incorporation of L33, L34, L16 into 50S ribosome [PUB_0224]; possibly involved in coupling 30S and 50S ribosomal subunits [PUB_0224];

Name: P200 protein
Comments: cytadherence [PUB_0089, PUB_0445]; similar to hmw1,3, but no significant sequence homology [PUB_0089]; high Pro content, low pI, central acidic Pro-rich domain as hmw1,3 [PUB_0089];

Name: GTP-binding protein Era
Comments: involved in last stage of ribosome maturation [PUB_0102]; 30S ribosome maturation, possibly by stabilizing helix 1 in 16S rRNA [PUB_0104, PUB_0105]; could control decision to initiate cell division  [PUB_0104]; may modulate division machinery as a function of 30S ribosome levels [PUB_0104];

Name: Putative metalloprotease
Comments: UPF0054 family [PUB_0096, PUB_0110];

Name: toxin ABC transporter, ATP-binding/permease protein
Comments: no predicted substrate binding protein in M. genitalium; bacteriocin/lantibiotic (eg. sublancin 168) exporter [PUB_0110, PUB_0241]; similar to multidrug resistant transporters of eukarya [PUB_0241]; no lantibiotic genes in M. genitalium;
Septation ring formation regulator, EzrA [PUB_0110]; two-component sensor histidine kinase vraS [PUB_0192];

Name: methionine-S-sulfoxide reductase
Comments: reactive oxygen species (eg. Superoxide, hydroxyl radical, hydrogen peroxide, singlet oxygen) can oxidize methionine to methionine sulfoxide; possibly > 30% of methionine residues are oxidized [PUB_0133]; catalyzes thioredoxin-dependent reduction of free and protein-bound Met(O) to methionine [PUB_0129]; S enantiomer selectivity [PUB_0131]; required for virulence, influences in cytadherence [PUB_0132];

Name: phosphate transport system regulatory protein PhoU, putative
Comments: negatively regulates phosphate ABC transporter (MG_410,MG_411,MG_412) when internal phosphate levels are elevated [PUB_0218];

Name: phosphate ABC transporter, permease protein PstA

Comments: Gene disruption mutants in MG414 have 16% faster doubling times than wild type M. genitalium [PUB_0182, PUB_0193];
Gene disruption mutants have faster doubling times than wild type M. genitalium [PUB_0193];

Name: DNA polymerase III, subunit gamma and tau

Comments: Gene disruption mutants in MG415 have faster doubling times than wild type M. genitalium [PUB_0193];

Name: metallo-beta-lactamase superfamily protein
Comments: beta-CASP family [PUB_0163]; lacks part of all the conserved amino acids that should be involved in the enzymatic function [PUB_0163];

Name: ATP-dependent RNA helicase
Comments: DEAD/DEAH box family [PUB_0061]; RNA unwinding for rRNA precursor processing (process 5' end of 23S rRNA precursor) [PUB_0061, PUB_0070], RNA degradosome (not present in M. gen) [PUB_0061, PUB_0068], repress and activate transcription [PUB_0069]; no specificity for particular RNA [PUB_0069]. Kinetic rate in B. subtilis 1.48 1/s [PUB_0688].

Name: osmotically inducible peroxidase
Comments: surface accesssible [PUB_0141]; may contribute to host adherence and colonization [PUB_0141]; more closely related to osmC than ohr [PUB_0143]; H2O2 and CHP can both serve as OsmC substrates [PUB_0145]; H2O2 is a relatively poor OsmC substrate [PUB_0145];

Name: LuxR bacterial regulatory protein, putative
Comments: Canonical luxIR qourum sensing system (eg. V. fischeri)LuxI synthase produces N-acyl homoserine lactones (AHL) [PUB_0208]LuxR is comprised of two functional domains: N-terminal signal-binding domain and a C-terminal DNA-binding domain [PUB_0208]LuxR signal-binding domain binds AHL and dimerizes [PUB_0209]LuxR dimer functions as either transcriptional activator or repressor [PUB_0208]:        Activator: AHL-LuxR dimer binds lux boxes at -40 from transcription start sites and recruits RNA polymerase    Repressor: AHL-luxR dimer binds promoters and blocks RNA polymerase [PUB_0208]    In the absence of AHL some LuxR-type proteins function as transcriptional repressors [PUB_0208]Consensus lux box: A[CA]CTGTAA[AT][AT]*T[TGA]ACAG[GT]T [PUB_0505]Orphan luxR systemsAHLs are most prevalent activating signal fororphan LuxR homologs [PUB_0208]Other signals can also activate orphan luxR homologs [PUB_0208]M. genitalium luxRNo luxI homologLike B. subtilis luxR homolog gerE MG_428 only has luxR C-terminal DNA binding domain [PUB_0110, PUB_0210]In B. subtilis GerE acts with _K to regulate coat gene for sporulation [PUB_0210]. However no _K is present in M. genitalium.Knockouts grow faster than wild-type [PUB_0193].M. genitalium luxR homologsIn addition to luxR family genes, MG_428 homologs include ECF-type sigma factors [PUB_0110].

Name: ribosome recycling factor
Comments: dissociates ribosome, deacylated tRNA, and mRNA after termination [PUB_0110, PUB_0226]; binds at ribosome A-site and mimics tRNA [PUB_0110]; formation of new ribosome complex may be limited by dissociation of old complexes [PUB_0229];

Name: type I restriction modification DNA specificity domain protein
Comments: MG_428 is homologous to the S subunit of EcoD hsd type I restriction/modification system [PUB_0097]. MG_428 is also similar to the small domain of the Type II N6-adenine DNA MTase TaqI [PUB_0097].hsd type I restriction/modification systemType I restriction modification systems methylate the N6 position of adenines of hemimethylated DNA, and cleave unmethylated DNA. S subunit has DNA sequence specificity [PUB_0097]. M subunit has modification activity [PUB_0097]. R subunit has ATP-dependent restrictase activity [PUB_0097]. Restriction occurs as remote sites from the recognition site [PUB_0542]. Restriction vs modification activity modulated by methylation status of DNA: hemimethylated DNA is modified, unmethylated DNA is cleaved, methylated DNA is not modified. Holoenzyme has composition S1M2R2 [PUB_0097, PUB_0652, PUB_0653].

Name: ribosomal biogenesis GTPase
Comments: related to P-loop GTPases era, engA but circularly permuted [PUB_0110]; required for late step of 50S ribosome assembly, complexation of L16 (and possibly L26, L36) protein with 45S ribosome subunit (50S ribosome subunit missing these r-proteins) [PUB_0222, PUB_0104];

Name: tRNA (guanine-N1)-methyltransferase
Comments: methylates G at 37th position of Leu (CUN, MG508, MG519), Pro (CCN, MG484), Arg (CGG, MG497) tRNAs [PUB_0048]

Name: multidrug efflux pump
Comments: Na+-driven multidrug efflux pump [PUB_0110]; mediate resistance to a range of cationic dyes, aminoglycosides and fluoroquinolones [PUB_0240, PUB_0241];

Name: methionine-R-sulfoxide reductase
Comments: reactive oxygen species (eg. Superoxide, hydroxyl radical, hydrogen peroxide, singlet oxygen) can oxidize methionine to methionine sulfoxide; possibly > 30% of methionine residues are oxidized [PUB_0133]; catalyzes thioredoxin-dependent reduction of free and protein-bound Met(O) to methionine [PUB_0129]; R enantiomer selectivity [PUB_0131];

Name: degV family protein
Comments: molecular function of fatty-acid binding and may play a role in the cellular functions of fatty acid transport or metabolism [PUB_0110]; may have kinase activity [PUB_0154];

Name: thiol-dependent peroxidase
Comments: surface accesssible [PUB_0141]; may contribute to host adherence and colonization [PUB_0141]; more closely related to ohr than osmC [PUB_0142]; not elevated in response to oxidative stress [PUB_0143]; elevated in response to physical stress -- eg. salt, heat [PUB_0143]; hydroperoxide reductase [PUB_0144]; metabolizes organic hydroperoxides (t-BHP and CHP) over inorganic H2O2 [PUB_0144];

Name: ATP-dependent metalloprotease FtsH
Comments: ftsH is a ATP-dependent, membrane bound metalloprotease which has been implicated in several processesDegradation of ssrA-tagged polypeptidesMolecular chaperone for integral membrane proteins [PUB_0014]Dislocation of misfolded membrane proteins from the membrane [PUB_0018]Cell-division [PUB_0510]FtsH is a bidirectionally processive protease [PUB_0030]. FtsH preferentially cleaves hydrophilic and basic residues [PUB_0030]. Produces fragments 10-20 aa's [PUB_0030]. Cleaves at rate 1.8 1/min [PUB_0031]. Requires 8 ATP per 18 hydrolyzed peptide bonds [PUB_0030], 8.3 ATP/cleavage [PUB_0031].

Name: putative 2-C-methyl-D-erythritol-2,4-cyclodiphosphate synthase
Comments: may encode a 2C-methyl-D-erythritol 2,4-cyclodiphosphate synthase [PUB_0182]; however M. genitalium does not synthesize isoprenyl pyrophosphate via deoxyxylulose [PUB_0182]; has none of other genes in Deoxyxylulose phosphate or Mevalonate pathways [PUB_0197];

Name: HD domain protein
Comments: Metal dependent phosphohydrolases with conserved 'HD' motif [PUB_0110]; family includes dGTPase, spoT guanosine polyphosphate [ppGpp(p)] hydrolase [PUB_0161];

Name: dimethyladenosine transferase
Comments: catalyzes m62A1518 and m62A1519 modifications of 16S rRNA [PUB_0105]; may have DNA glycosylase / AP lyase activity for C mispaired with oxidized T [PUB_0105, PUB_0106]; may act as quality control element segregating mature from immature 30S ribosomes [PUB_0105];

Name: inner-membrane protein insertion factor
Comments: mediates transfer of transmembrane segements (TMs) from the translocase (secYE) into the lipid bilayer [PUB_0016]; interacts with secYE with 1:1 stoichiometry [PUB_0006]; functions as independent membrane protein insertase, particularly for energy-transducing membrane proteins [PUB_0018]; provides an amphiphilic surface that shields charged residues and TMSs from the hydrophobic acyl chain environment and charged lipid headgroups [PUB_0017];

Name: ribonuclease P protein component
Comments: Endonuclease [PUB_0044]. Cleaves 5' ends of tRNA and tmRNA [PUB_0039]. Kinetic rate in B. subtilis 0.027 1/s [PUB_0013], 6 1/s [PUB_0690].

Name: salivaricin A ABC transporter, ATP-binding protein
Comments: no predicted substrate binding protein in M. genitalium; macrolide-specific ABC transporter [PUB_0110, PUB_0440]; salivaricin A is a lantibiotic; no lantibiotic genes in M. genitalium;

Name: salivaricin A ABC transporter, permease protein
Comments: no predicted substrate binding protein in M. genitalium; macrolide-specific ABC transporter [PUB_0110, PUB_0440]; salivaricin A is a lantibiotic; no lantibiotic genes in M. genitalium;

Name: salivaricin A ABC transporter, ATP-binding protein
Comments: no predicted substrate binding protein in M. genitalium; macrolide-specific ABC transporter [PUB_0110, PUB_0440]; salivaricin A is a lantibiotic; no lantibiotic genes in M. genitalium;

Name: CobQ/CobB/MinD/ParA nucleotide binding domain
Comments: ATPases involved in chromosome partitioning [PUB_0110]; Soj is a transcriptional regulator and can repress the expression of several early stage sporulation genes [PUB_0135]; parB not present in M. genitalium; parB binds to several specific sites close to the origin of DNA replication [PUB_0135]; in the presence of Soj, the small complexes of bound Spo0J (parB) are condensed into compact foci [PUB_0135]; ATP-dependent dimerization [PUB_0335];
